{"title": "compile_path silently drops port from host route regex", "description": "For host routes, `path[idx:].split(':')[0]` strips everything after ':' from the remaining literal text, discarding port specifications. A host pattern like '{subdomain}.example.com:8080' compiles to regex matching only '.example.com$' but path_format retains ':8080'. This causes: (1) routes with explicit ports never match (regex expects $ after hostname), (2) url_path_for generates URLs with the port that the regex can't match back.", "severity": "P1", "old_string": "    if is_host:
        hostname = path[idx:].split(":")[0]
        path_regex += re.escape(hostname) + "$"", "new_string": "    if is_host:
        path_regex += re.escape(path[idx:]) + "$"", "invariant": "compile_path regex and format string must represent the same pattern; silently discarding segments breaks round-trip consistency"}
{"title": "replace_params vulnerable to double-substitution injection", "description": "replace_params replaces parameter placeholders sequentially using str.replace(). If a parameter's converted value contains a substring matching another parameter's placeholder (e.g., id='{name}'), the value is re-substituted when the next parameter is processed. For path_format='/users/{id}/{name}' with id='{name}' and name='hello', the result is '/users/hello/hello' instead of the expected '/users/{name}/hello'. This corrupts generated URLs when parameter values contain curly-brace patterns.", "severity": "P2", "old_string": "def replace_params(path, param_convertors, path_params):
    for key, value in list(path_params.items()):
        if "{" + key + "}" in path:
            convertor = param_convertors[key]
            value = convertor.to_string(value)
            path = path.replace("{" + key + "}", value)
            path_params.pop(key)
    return path, path_params", "new_string": "def replace_params(path, param_convertors, path_params):
    for key, value in list(path_params.items()):
        placeholder = "{" + key + "}"
        if placeholder in path:
            convertor = param_convertors[key]
            value = convertor.to_string(value)
            # Replace only the first occurrence per iteration to avoid
            # double-substitution; compile_path rejects duplicate params
            # so at most one occurrence exists in the original format.
            parts = path.split(placeholder, 1)
            path = parts[0] + value + parts[1]
            path_params.pop(key)
    return path, path_params", "invariant": "URL generation must treat converted parameter values as opaque strings, never re-interpreting them as template placeholders"}
